caption: Good beer here but had a terrible experience with the manager. We had a work event and one colleague showed up without proper ID. When he asked if alternative ID was okay, the manager started screaming and using the F word. Out of control and not proportionate. Would not recommend, plenty of options near by.

Great hosting, delicious food with a satisfying variety of beverages, and a well designed open environment. I would recommend to anyone wanting a nice place to go for drinks with friends or watch the big game!

Last Saturday, I spent time with 5 others at one of the tables with a fire pit (reservation required) to celebrate a friend's birthday. The staff checked our IDs and took our numbers for contact tracing. They also made it clear that masks should be worn at all times unless we are at our tables eating and drinking. Although we were seated outdoors, they were serious about a 6-person limit per table and discouraged spending time away from our designated table. The servers come to the table frequently so there is no need to aporoach the bar. I felt very safe in this environment. In additon, their mulled hot cider (with whiskey) was divine!!

The only reason it’s two stars and not one is that the food was decent and not awfully expensive but not cheap. The staff was a mix between disorganized and rude between all of them. I genuinely would not recommend this place. Maybe it’s better pre-pandemic but in its current state it was a genuinely unpleasant time.

Rude disorganized staff couldn't follow through on a simple reservation and were unwilling to help or accommodate after their initial mistake. The host/bouncer was particularly unprofessional. Don't waste your time or money!

James had us waiting for more than 30 mins outside before telling us we can’t get inside. Told us to forward my complaint to the owner, Robin Webv. Total waste of time.

Short story: this place is so "popular" that the staff doesn't care about your patronage. I'd recommend to Hook Hall across the street instead.  Long story: Today (Saturday, January 9th) I tried making a reservation for 2 on Midlands' preferred platform, Resy. I knew they would be busy because it's a sunny day, and they're one of the few spots in Petworth with outdoor seating. On the Midlands' website for reservations, Resy showed a few times available between 6 and 8pm. I tried making reserving one of those spots, but for every time showed as "available" an error message would pop up saying that "this time is no longer available". Yet, when I returned to the site to check the other open times, they still gave the same message.  SO we decided to stop by in person, and see if we could make the reservation in person or at least get put on the waitlist. We wait our turn for the hostess, and when we ask about the waitlist, she says they're busy until 6pm. She told us she couldn't put us on the waitlist. We said "ok, so can we make a reservation for later instead?" She told us that we would have to go on the Resy site, so we told her AND SHOWED her that the site wasn't working. She told us that it's not her problem, that it's a problem with Resy, and that she "can't do anything about it." We asked if she could book us in from her end manually: "no", so we asked if she could put our name on the waitlist for after 6pm "no, because the system isn't working."  When we asked to speak with Midlands management, she declined and said they would tell us the exact same thing. We said: "ok, so what do we need to do to get put on the waitlist or get a reservation?" This hostess made it sound like it was impossible. She told us that we will have to come back at 6pm and try our luck then. She also said to keep trying the Resy system (even though we showed her it's not working), and that again - not their problem. I was shocked, because I've never had bad service here. Why didn't management figure out a new way to book people when their primary system isn't working? Seems like Midlands is indifferent to whether or not you patronize them.
The bar staff is absolutely rude. Do yourself a favor and go across the street to Hook Hall.

Yelling at adult customers is totally unacceptable. Our waitress was awful and was biased. The food tasted terrible. I asked if my friend who had been waiting in line to enter with me, but had to leave to move his car (during which I reached the front of the line and entered) could enter without having to wait in line again. The answer was no and I totally respect that, but wish he had communicated it in a nice, or at least less jerky, way. He was rude and condescending. It doesn’t hurt to be respectful to your customers!!!  Edited to add: I appreciate the response from the owner. I’ve been back a few times and the bouncers (different people) were very nice. Jimmy Eat World, a band beloved by some and forgotten by others, once had a song called ‘The Middle’. Sure, I may not remember the verses and only have a vague recollection of the chorus, but I still appreciate it nevertheless for the fact that it celebrates something that’s rather easy to ignore, namely ‘the middle’. It’s a place most would rather not pay attention to. Has anyone ever paid extra for a middle seat in an airplane? Sure, a sandwich needs meat and vegetables, but they are often ignored in favor of the bread that surrounds them.  Now comes the Midlands, a bar that is proudly dedicated towards ‘the middle’. We may agree, we may also disagree, but it’s a place we can always meet. Smart marketing, if you ask me. The seats are good. The outdoor patio offers views of clouds, sky, sun, stars and the occasional passing satellite, airplane and helicopter.  I had the beer. I liked it.

I want to love this place. I do. It has such good bones. The space is large, the barbecue tasty if not slightly overpriced. But their beer menu, the reason we're all here, has always been underwhelming. It's not that the quality of the beer itself is low - I generally will find something on the list that's worth trying - their rotation is completely out of sync with the season. An overabundance of stouts in the summer, witbier in winter, I'm usually at a loss of what to try that will satisfy. I don't know if their sourcing is routinely delayed, or if my seasonal tastes simply differ, but my experience always ends up as a miss.
